-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- CHAPTERS 6 – 10
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 6 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 6, 'kids', 1, 'What prayer did Jesus teach his disciples in Matthew 6?', 'The Lord''s Prayer (Our Father)', 'The Shema', 'The Aaronic Blessing', 'A Psalm of David', 'a', 'Matthew 6:9-13 — "After this manner therefore pray ye: Our Father which art in heaven..." This is known as the Lord''s Prayer.'),
('Matthew', 6, 'kids', 2, 'Jesus says we cannot serve two masters. What two masters does he mention?', 'God and mammon', 'God and Caesar', 'Heaven and earth', 'Angels and men', 'a', 'Matthew 6:24 — "Ye cannot serve God and mammon."'),
('Matthew', 6, 'kids', 3, 'What does Jesus say about the flowers of the field?', 'Not even Solomon was dressed as gloriously as they', 'They grow only in the promised land', 'God planted them for our food', 'They remind us to pray every day', 'a', 'Matthew 6:29 — "And yet I say unto you, That even Solomon in all his glory was not arrayed like one of these."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 6, 'teens', 1, 'Jesus warns against doing charitable deeds to be seen by others. What does he call those who do?', 'Hypocrites who have their reward already', 'Sinners who need more prayer', 'Fools who waste their gifts', 'Proud men who will be humbled', 'a', 'Matthew 6:2 — "Therefore when thou doest thine alms, do not sound a trumpet before thee, as the hypocrites do in the synagogues and in the streets, that they may have glory of men. Verily I say unto you, They have their reward."'),
('Matthew', 6, 'teens', 2, 'What does Jesus say about storing up treasure on earth versus in heaven?', 'Store up treasure in heaven where moth and rust cannot corrupt', 'Wealth on earth is a sign of God''s blessing', 'Store equal amounts in both places', 'Treasure on earth is acceptable if tithed from', 'a', 'Matthew 6:19-20 — "Lay not up for yourselves treasures upon earth, where moth and rust doth corrupt...But lay up for yourselves treasures in heaven, where neither moth nor rust doth corrupt."'),
('Matthew', 6, 'teens', 3, 'What does "hallowed be thy name" mean in the Lord''s Prayer?', 'May your name be kept holy and revered', 'Please tell us your name', 'We are holy because of your name', 'Keep our names in your book', 'a', 'Matthew 6:9 — "Hallowed be thy name." To hallow means to set apart as holy, to regard with reverence and worship.'),
('Matthew', 6, 'teens', 4, 'What does Jesus say about fasting in Matthew 6?', 'Fast secretly, not with a sad face to be seen by others', 'Fast on the same days as the Pharisees', 'Fasting is no longer required under grace', 'Fast publicly so others will also fast', 'a', 'Matthew 6:16-18 — "Moreover when ye fast, be not, as the hypocrites, of a sad countenance...But thou, when thou fastest, anoint thine head, and wash thy face; That thou appear not unto men to fast, but unto thy Father which is in secret."'),
('Matthew', 6, 'teens', 5, 'What does Jesus say about worrying (taking thought) for tomorrow?', 'Take no thought for the morrow; sufficient unto the day is the evil thereof', 'Plan carefully for the future but do not worry', 'Worry is sinful but unavoidable', 'Trust God but also save money', 'a', 'Matthew 6:34 — "Take therefore no thought for the morrow: for the morrow shall take thought for the things of itself. Sufficient unto the day is the evil thereof."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 6, 'adults', 1, 'What is the structural principle governing the three acts of piety (almsgiving, prayer, fasting) in Matthew 6:1-18?', 'Each is to be done in secret before the Father, contrasting the hypocrites'' public performance for human approval', 'Each requires a priest as witness to be valid', 'Each must be done in the temple to be accepted by God', 'Each increases in importance — fasting being the highest', 'a', 'Matthew 6:1 — "Take heed that ye do not your alms before men, to be seen of them: otherwise ye have no reward of your Father which is in heaven." All three sections follow the same pattern: hypocrites do it publicly → their earthly reward is all they get; do it secretly → Father rewards openly.'),
('Matthew', 6, 'adults', 2, 'The Lord''s Prayer petition "forgive us our debts, as we forgive our debtors" is immediately reinforced in verses 14-15. What is the theological implication?', 'Willingness to forgive others is evidence of having received forgiveness; withholding forgiveness calls one''s own forgiveness into question', 'We earn forgiveness by forgiving others', 'Our forgiveness of others is more important than God''s forgiveness of us', 'The petition is only for the disciples, not believers generally', 'a', 'Matthew 6:14-15 — "For if ye forgive men their trespasses, your heavenly Father will also forgive you: But if ye forgive not men their trespasses, neither will your Father forgive your trespasses." This is not earning forgiveness but the test of genuine repentance.'),
('Matthew', 6, 'adults', 3, 'What does "Thy kingdom come" mean in its eschatological and ethical dimensions?', 'It is a prayer for God''s reign to be fully realized — both in present obedience and in the final consummation', 'It is a prayer for the restoration of the Davidic monarchy', 'It refers only to a future millennial kingdom with no present application', 'It means we are asking to die and go to heaven', 'a', 'Matthew 6:10 — "Thy kingdom come. Thy will be done in earth, as it is in heaven." The petition has both a future eschatological dimension (the final coming of God''s rule) and a present ethical dimension (doing God''s will on earth as in heaven).'),
('Matthew', 6, 'adults', 4, 'What is the meaning of "epiousios" (daily/supersubstantial) bread in Matthew 6:11?', 'The Greek epiousios is debated — possibly "bread for today/tomorrow" (sustenance) or "supersubstantial bread" pointing to the Eucharist', 'It clearly means only physical food for the next twenty-four hours', 'It refers to the manna in the wilderness with no present application', 'It means luxurious or abundant bread', 'a', 'Matthew 6:11 — "Give us this day our daily bread." The Greek epiousios (found almost nowhere else in Greek literature) is unique; Jerome rendered it as "supersubstantial" in Latin. It likely means sufficient bread for the present day, though early church fathers saw a eucharistic dimension.'),
('Matthew', 6, 'adults', 5, 'How does Jesus'' teaching on the "single eye" (haplous) in 6:22-23 connect to the broader passage on serving God and mammon?', 'The single eye (undivided focus) illustrates wholehearted devotion to God; a divided eye represents the divided loyalty of serving both God and wealth', 'It teaches the importance of physical eye health', 'It refers to the eye as the lamp revealing others'' sins', 'It means one should look at only holy things', 'a', 'Matthew 6:22-24 — "The light of the body is the eye: if therefore thine eye be single (haplous — undivided/generous), thy whole body shall be full of light...Ye cannot serve God and mammon." The eye metaphor bridges the treasure passage (vv.19-21) and the mammon saying (v.24).'),
('Matthew', 6, 'adults', 6, 'What does "first seek the kingdom of God and his righteousness" (6:33) mean within the context of anxiety about material provision?', 'Prioritizing God''s reign and righteous living is the antidote to anxiety; all other necessities will be provided as a consequence', 'It means spiritual matters are the only things that matter and material life should be neglected', 'It is a prosperity gospel promise that seeking God guarantees wealth', 'It refers to seeking entrance to the literal kingdom in Jerusalem', 'a', 'Matthew 6:33 — "But seek ye first the kingdom of God, and his righteousness; and all these things shall be added unto you." The command directly addresses the anxiety of vv.25-32 — trusting the Father''s provision frees one for kingdom priorities.'),
('Matthew', 6, 'adults', 7, 'What is the significance of calling God "our Father which art in heaven" at the opening of the Lord''s Prayer?', 'It establishes both the intimacy of sonship (Father) and the transcendent sovereignty (in heaven) of God simultaneously', 'It means only the disciples who were present could use this prayer', 'It limits prayer to formal occasions in the temple', 'It implies God is physically located in a heavenly palace', 'a', 'Matthew 6:9 — The Aramaic "Abba" (Father) carries relational warmth unprecedented in Jewish public prayer forms, while "in heaven" preserves divine transcendence. Together they define the unique Christian relationship with God.'),
('Matthew', 6, 'adults', 8, 'How does the phrase "lead us not into temptation, but deliver us from evil" function theologically in the Lord''s Prayer?', 'It is a petition for God''s providential protection — acknowledging human weakness and dependence on divine deliverance from the Evil One', 'It implies God regularly leads people into sin', 'It is a prayer that sin would not exist in the world', 'It refers only to external physical dangers', 'a', 'Matthew 6:13 — "And lead us not into temptation, but deliver us from evil (or the evil one)." The petition acknowledges that disciples face real spiritual danger and are entirely dependent on God''s guidance and protection, not their own moral strength.');

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 7 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 7, 'kids', 1, 'Jesus says to ask, seek, and ___.', 'Knock', 'Pray', 'Believe', 'Wait', 'a', 'Matthew 7:7 — "Ask, and it shall be given you; seek, and ye shall find; knock, and it shall be opened unto you."'),
('Matthew', 7, 'kids', 2, 'What is the Golden Rule that Jesus teaches in Matthew 7?', 'Do unto others as you would have them do unto you', 'Love the Lord your God with all your heart', 'Honour your father and mother', 'Love your neighbour as yourself', 'a', 'Matthew 7:12 — "Therefore all things whatsoever ye would that men should do to you, do ye even so to them: for this is the law and the prophets."'),
('Matthew', 7, 'kids', 3, 'A wise man builds his house on what?', 'A rock', 'Sand', 'Wood', 'A hill', 'a', 'Matthew 7:24 — "Therefore whosoever heareth these sayings of mine, and doeth them, I will liken him unto a wise man, which built his house upon a rock."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 7, 'teens', 1, 'What does Jesus warn about the wide gate and the broad way?', 'Many enter by it and it leads to destruction', 'It leads to the kingdom but requires more effort', 'Only Gentiles use it', 'It is for the physically weak', 'a', 'Matthew 7:13 — "Enter ye in at the strait gate: for wide is the gate, and broad is the way, that leadeth to destruction, and many there be which go in thereat."'),
('Matthew', 7, 'teens', 2, 'How can you recognize a false prophet, according to Jesus?', 'By their fruits', 'By their clothing', 'By whether they perform miracles', 'By their nationality', 'a', 'Matthew 7:16 — "Ye shall know them by their fruits. Do men gather grapes of thorns, or figs of thistles?"'),
('Matthew', 7, 'teens', 3, 'What will Jesus say to those who prophesied and cast out demons in his name but whom he never knew?', 'Depart from me, ye that work iniquity', 'Well done, good and faithful servants', 'You lacked faith; try again', 'Enter into the kingdom as second-class citizens', 'a', 'Matthew 7:23 — "And then will I profess unto them, I never knew you: depart from me, ye that work iniquity."'),
('Matthew', 7, 'teens', 4, 'What happens to the foolish man''s house built on sand?', 'It fell, and great was the fall of it', 'It stood but leaked badly', 'It was swept away slowly over years', 'It was moved to a safer location', 'a', 'Matthew 7:27 — "And the rain descended, and the floods came, and the winds blew, and beat upon that house; and it fell: and great was the fall of it."'),
('Matthew', 7, 'teens', 5, 'What was the reaction of the people to Jesus'' teaching at the end of the Sermon on the Mount?', 'They were astonished because he taught with authority, not as the scribes', 'They rejected his teaching and left', 'They asked him to explain the law of Moses', 'They praised the scribes who agreed with him', 'a', 'Matthew 7:28-29 — "the people were astonished at his doctrine: For he taught them as one having authority, and not as the scribes."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 7, 'adults', 1, 'What does "Judge not, that ye be not judged" (7:1) actually prohibit in its context?', 'Hypocritical, self-righteous judgment that ignores one''s own sins — not all discernment or moral assessment', 'All forms of moral evaluation or church discipline', 'Legal courts and civil justice', 'Forming any opinions about other people''s behavior', 'a', 'Matthew 7:1-5 — The context of the speck and beam shows Jesus targets self-righteous hypocrisy. Verse 5 commands removing one''s own beam first, then helping the brother — implying that righteous, humble correction is expected after self-examination.'),
('Matthew', 7, 'adults', 2, 'The warning "Give not that which is holy unto the dogs, neither cast pearls before swine" (7:6) creates what interpretive tension with the command to judge not (7:1)?', 'It shows that disciples must exercise discernment to identify those who persistently reject the gospel, requiring wise discrimination', 'It has no connection to the preceding passage', 'It refers to the Gentile mission being inappropriate', 'It is hyperbole meaning believers should never share the gospel', 'a', 'Matthew 7:6 — After commanding against hypocritical judgment, Jesus commands a different kind of discernment — recognizing persistent hostility to holy things. This shows "judge not" is not abolishing discernment but purifying its motive.'),
('Matthew', 7, 'adults', 3, 'How does the ask/seek/knock promise (7:7-11) relate to the broader Sermon on the Mount?', 'It assures disciples that the demanding ethical standards of the Sermon are achievable through prayer — God gives good gifts to those who ask', 'It is a separate teaching about material prosperity with no connection to the Sermon', 'It promises that all requests without condition will be granted', 'It is directed only to the twelve apostles', 'a', 'Matthew 7:7-11 — After the challenging ethical demands of chapters 5-7, the ask/seek/knock promise encourages disciples that the Father will provide what is needed to live the kingdom life. The conclusion (v.11) compares God''s generosity favorably to even evil human fathers.'),
('Matthew', 7, 'adults', 4, 'What does the metaphor of "sheep''s clothing" on wolves signify in the false prophet warning (7:15)?', 'False prophets use the external appearance of piety and Christian identity to conceal destructive teaching', 'Wolves represent Roman soldiers persecuting the church', 'The warning is about physical threats to shepherds', 'It means true prophets will dress differently from false ones', 'a', 'Matthew 7:15 — "Beware of false prophets, which come to you in sheep''s clothing, but inwardly they are ravening wolves." The sheep''s clothing represents religious appearance — they look like members of the flock while inwardly predatory.'),
('Matthew', 7, 'adults', 5, 'Why does Matthew place the double standard of the broad/narrow way (7:13-14) immediately after the Golden Rule (7:12)?', 'The Golden Rule summarizes the Law and Prophets, and the narrow way is the difficult path of actually living it — requiring commitment few are willing to make', 'Matthew randomly ordered the teachings for narrative flow', 'The narrow way refers to Jewish dietary restrictions', 'The Golden Rule leads naturally to the broad way of tolerance', 'a', 'Matthew 7:12-14 — The Golden Rule closes the ethical instruction ("this is the law and the prophets"), and immediately the narrow gate confronts disciples with the hard reality that genuinely living this standard is a difficult, counter-cultural path chosen by few.'),
('Matthew', 7, 'adults', 6, 'What is the Christological significance of Jesus'' self-reference as judge in 7:22-23 ("I will profess unto them, I never knew you")?', 'Jesus claims divine prerogative as eschatological judge, implicitly equating himself with the God of judgment in OT prophecy', 'Jesus is merely predicting what God the Father will say', 'It is a reference to the judgment of angels, not humans', 'Jesus is speaking as a prophet, not as judge', 'a', 'Matthew 7:22-23 — "Many will say to me in that day, Lord, Lord...And then will I profess unto them, I never knew you." Jesus positions himself as the final judge of all humanity — an implicit claim to divine authority consistent with his "but I say unto you" antitheses throughout the Sermon.'),
('Matthew', 7, 'adults', 7, 'What does the parable of the two builders (7:24-27) use as its criterion for wisdom versus foolishness?', 'Hearing and doing Jesus'' words versus hearing without obedience', 'Intellectual agreement with sound doctrine versus heresy', 'Being baptized versus being unbaptized', 'Church membership versus non-membership', 'a', 'Matthew 7:24, 26 — "whosoever heareth these sayings of mine, and doeth them" versus "every one that heareth these sayings of mine, and doeth them not." The parable''s criterion is not hearing but doing — the same storm destroys the foolish house as tests the wise one.'),
('Matthew', 7, 'adults', 8, 'How does the crowd''s astonishment at Jesus'' "authority" (exousia) in 7:28-29 contrast with the scribes'' teaching method?', 'Scribes cited earlier authorities (rabbinical tradition); Jesus spoke on his own authority — "I say unto you" — claiming direct divine authorization', 'The scribes taught with miracles; Jesus taught only with words', 'The scribes spoke loudly; Jesus spoke quietly', 'The crowd preferred the scribes but was momentarily impressed by Jesus', 'a', 'Matthew 7:29 — "he taught them as one having authority, and not as the scribes." Scribes typically said "Rabbi X said...Rabbi Y said..." Jesus'' "But I say unto you" throughout the Sermon was unprecedented — speaking in his own name as the final authority on divine revelation.');

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 8 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 8, 'kids', 1, 'What disease did Jesus heal the man of at the beginning of Matthew 8?', 'Leprosy', 'Blindness', 'Deafness', 'Paralysis', 'a', 'Matthew 8:2-3 — "And, behold, there came a leper and worshipped him...And Jesus put forth his hand, and touched him, saying, I will; be thou clean. And immediately his leprosy was cleansed."'),
('Matthew', 8, 'kids', 2, 'What did Jesus do when he was in the boat and a great storm came?', 'He rebuked the wind and the sea and there was a great calm', 'He prayed for three hours', 'He asked his disciples to help', 'He guided the boat to shore', 'a', 'Matthew 8:26 — "Then he arose, and rebuked the winds and the sea; and there was a great calm."'),
('Matthew', 8, 'kids', 3, 'Where were the disciples when Jesus calmed the storm?', 'In a ship on the sea', 'On the shore', 'In a fishing boat near land', 'Swimming in the water', 'a', 'Matthew 8:23-24 — "And when he was entered into a ship, his disciples followed him. And, behold, there arose a great tempest in the sea."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 8, 'teens', 1, 'What amazed Jesus about the centurion''s faith?', 'He had not found such great faith in all Israel', 'The centurion had healed sick people himself', 'He had memorized all the Scriptures', 'He had already built a synagogue', 'a', 'Matthew 8:10 — "When Jesus heard it, he marvelled, and said to them that followed, Verily I say unto you, I have not found so great faith, no, not in Israel."'),
('Matthew', 8, 'teens', 2, 'What did the centurion say he was not worthy of?', 'That Jesus should come under his roof', 'Meeting Jesus in the temple', 'Having his servant healed', 'Being baptized by John', 'a', 'Matthew 8:8 — "The centurion answered and said, Lord, I am not worthy that thou shouldest come under my roof: but speak the word only, and my servant shall be healed."'),
('Matthew', 8, 'teens', 3, 'What did the two demon-possessed men say to Jesus when he came to their country?', '"Art thou come hither to torment us before the time?"', '"We know who you are, Jesus of Galilee"', '"Have mercy on us, Lord, Son of David"', '"We will follow you wherever you go"', 'a', 'Matthew 8:29 — "And, behold, they cried out, saying, What have we to do with thee, Jesus, thou Son of God? art thou come hither to torment us before the time?"'),
('Matthew', 8, 'teens', 4, 'What happened to the herd of pigs after Jesus cast the demons into them?', 'They ran violently down a steep place into the sea and perished', 'They became calm and lay down', 'They ran into the city', 'They disappeared into the hills', 'a', 'Matthew 8:32 — "And he said unto them, Go. And when they were come out, they went into the herd of swine: and, behold, the whole herd of swine ran violently down a steep place into the sea, and perished in the waters."'),
('Matthew', 8, 'teens', 5, 'Jesus said the Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head. What was the context of this statement?', 'A scribe said he would follow Jesus wherever he went', 'Jesus was explaining his birth in a manger', 'The disciples complained about their sleeping arrangements', 'Jesus was refusing entry into the temple', 'a', 'Matthew 8:19-20 — "And a certain scribe came, and said unto him, Master, I will follow thee whithersoever thou goest. And Jesus saith unto him, The foxes have holes, and the birds of the air have nests; but the Son of man hath not where to lay his head."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 8, 'adults', 1, 'Why does Jesus tell the healed leper to show himself to the priest and offer the gift Moses commanded (8:4)?', 'To fulfill the Levitical purification rite (Lev 14) that formally reinstated the healed person to the community', 'To prove that Jesus respected the Pharisees'' authority', 'As a test to see if the priest would accept a miracle', 'To prevent the leper from telling others about the healing', 'a', 'Matthew 8:4 — "See thou tell no man; but go thy way, shew thyself to the priest, and offer the gift that Moses commanded, for a testimony unto them." The Mosaic law (Lev 14) required an examination and offering to restore social and ritual standing to a healed leper.'),
('Matthew', 8, 'adults', 2, 'What is the eschatological significance of Jesus'' statement about many coming from east and west to sit with Abraham at the feast (8:11)?', 'It predicts the ingathering of Gentiles into the messianic banquet while some natural heirs of the kingdom are excluded', 'It teaches that all Jews will be saved in the end', 'It refers only to the twelve tribes of Israel being reunited', 'It describes life in heaven with no application to Gentiles', 'a', 'Matthew 8:11-12 — "And I say unto you, That many shall come from the east and west, and shall sit down with Abraham, and Isaac, and Jacob, in the kingdom of heaven. But the children of the kingdom shall be cast out." The centurion''s faith occasions a prediction of Gentile inclusion and Jewish exclusion based on faith, not ethnicity.'),
('Matthew', 8, 'adults', 3, 'What does Jesus'' touch of the leper (8:3) signify given Jewish purity laws that declared such contact defiling?', 'Jesus reverses the direction of contagion — instead of impurity transferring to him, his holiness cleanses the leper', 'Jesus violated the law to show he was above it', 'The leper was technically clean already', 'Jesus performed the touch as a teaching method only', 'a', 'Matthew 8:3 — "And Jesus put forth his hand, and touched him." Leviticus 5:2-3 declared anyone touching a leper unclean. But Jesus'' touch flows the other direction — "immediately his leprosy was cleansed." This demonstrates that his power to cleanse exceeds the power of defilement to pollute.'),
('Matthew', 8, 'adults', 4, 'How does the healing of Peter''s mother-in-law (8:14-15) illustrate the purpose of divine healing in Matthew''s theology?', 'Restoration leads to service — she arose and ministered unto them, showing healing enables renewed Kingdom service', 'It proves that women could be disciples of Jesus', 'It establishes that miraculous healing is guaranteed for all believers', 'It demonstrates Jesus'' preference for healing private cases over public ones', 'a', 'Matthew 8:15 — "And he touched her hand, and the fever left her: and she arose, and ministered unto them." The immediate response of service shows that healing in Matthew''s gospel is not merely humanitarian but restores people to purposeful discipleship.'),
('Matthew', 8, 'adults', 5, 'Matthew 8:17 quotes Isaiah 53:4 — "Himself took our infirmities, and bare our sicknesses." How does Matthew apply this Servant Song to Jesus'' healing ministry?', 'Jesus'' physical healings are a foretaste and expression of the vicarious suffering he bears on behalf of humanity', 'Matthew restricts Isaiah 53 to physical healing only, not spiritual atonement', 'Matthew sees Jesus as a physician rather than a sacrifice', 'It means Jesus got sick while healing others', 'a', 'Matthew 8:17 — citing Isaiah 53:4. Matthew sees Jesus'' compassionate healings as the beginning of his Servant mission — bearing human brokenness. The full bearing of sin at the cross extends what begins here in the healing of bodies.'),
('Matthew', 8, 'adults', 6, 'What does the disciples'' question "What manner of man is this, that even the winds and the sea obey him?" (8:27) echo from the OT?', 'Psalms 89:9 and 107:25-29 where God alone commands the sea and stills the storm', 'The account of Elijah calling down rain', 'Moses'' parting of the Red Sea', 'Jonah''s prayer from the belly of the fish', 'a', 'Matthew 8:27 — The question echoes OT divine prerogatives. Psalm 89:9 — "Thou rulest the raging of the sea: when the waves thereof arise, thou stillest them." Psalm 107:29 — "He maketh the storm a calm." The disciples'' question implicitly points to Jesus'' divine identity.'),
('Matthew', 8, 'adults', 7, 'The demons'' recognition of Jesus as "Son of God" and their mention of "the time" (8:29) reveals what theological understanding?', 'Demons know Jesus'' identity and understand that at the appointed eschatological time their torment will be final — they fear premature judgment', 'Demons are confused about Jesus'' identity', 'The demons believed in Jesus and were therefore saved', 'The time refers to the day of the resurrection', 'a', 'Matthew 8:29 — "art thou come hither to torment us before the time?" The demons acknowledge both Jesus'' divine sonship and an appointed time for their final judgment (Revelation 20:10), fearing that Jesus would execute final judgment prematurely.'),
('Matthew', 8, 'adults', 8, 'What does the reaction of the entire city of the Gadarenes — asking Jesus to leave — reveal about the cost of Jesus'' kingdom presence?', 'When kingdom power disrupts economic and social order, worldly comfort is preferred over the presence of the Savior', 'The Gadarenes were demon-worshippers who feared God', 'The people were afraid because they misunderstood the miracle', 'Jesus left voluntarily before being asked', 'a', 'Matthew 8:34 — "And, behold, the whole city came out to meet Jesus: and when they saw him, they besought him that he would depart out of their coasts." The loss of the pig herd (representing economic loss) led the entire city to reject Jesus, illustrating that worldly interests often outweigh spiritual opportunity.');

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 9 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 9, 'kids', 1, 'What did Jesus say to the paralyzed man before healing him?', 'Son, be of good cheer; thy sins be forgiven thee', 'Rise up and walk immediately', 'Your faith has made you whole', 'Take up your bed and go home now', 'a', 'Matthew 9:2 — "And, behold, they brought to him a man sick of the palsy, lying on a bed: and Jesus seeing their faith said unto the sick of the palsy; Son, be of good cheer; thy sins be forgiven thee."'),
('Matthew', 9, 'kids', 2, 'What was Matthew''s job before Jesus called him?', 'A tax collector', 'A fisherman', 'A carpenter', 'A priest', 'a', 'Matthew 9:9 — "And as Jesus passed forth from thence, he saw a man, named Matthew, sitting at the receipt of custom: and he saith unto him, Follow me. And he arose, and followed him."'),
('Matthew', 9, 'kids', 3, 'What did Jesus say the sick need, not the healthy?', 'A physician', 'A teacher', 'A priest', 'A prophet', 'a', 'Matthew 9:12 — "They that be whole need not a physician, but they that are sick."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 9, 'teens', 1, 'What do the scribes accuse Jesus of when he forgives the paralyzed man''s sins?', 'Blasphemy', 'Breaking the Sabbath', 'False prophecy', 'Sorcery', 'a', 'Matthew 9:3 — "And, behold, certain of the scribes said within themselves, This man blasphemeth." They understood that only God can forgive sins, so they accused Jesus of blasphemy for claiming this prerogative.'),
('Matthew', 9, 'teens', 2, 'What did the ruler ask Jesus to do for his daughter?', 'Come and lay his hand on her and she would live', 'Pray for her healing from a distance', 'Send his disciples to anoint her', 'Bring her to the temple for prayer', 'a', 'Matthew 9:18 — "My daughter is even now dead: but come and lay thy hand upon her, and she shall live."'),
('Matthew', 9, 'teens', 3, 'How was the woman with the issue of blood healed?', 'She touched the hem of Jesus'' garment', 'Jesus spoke a word of healing over her', 'She was anointed with oil by the disciples', 'She washed in the pool as Jesus commanded', 'a', 'Matthew 9:20-22 — "a woman, which was diseased with an issue of blood twelve years, came behind him, and touched the hem of his garment...And Jesus turned him about, and when he saw her, he said, Daughter, be of good comfort; thy faith hath made thee whole."'),
('Matthew', 9, 'teens', 4, 'When Jesus healed the two blind men, what question did he ask them first?', 'Believe ye that I am able to do this?', 'What do you want me to do for you?', 'How long have you been blind?', 'Do you want to be made whole?', 'a', 'Matthew 9:28 — "And when he was come into the house, the blind men came to him: and Jesus saith unto them, Believe ye that I am able to do this? They said unto him, Yea, Lord."'),
('Matthew', 9, 'teens', 5, 'What does Jesus say about new wine and old bottles (wineskins)?', 'New wine must be put into new bottles else the bottles break', 'Old wine is always better than new wine', 'New wine should be shared with both old and young', 'Wine is forbidden but is used as a metaphor for teaching', 'a', 'Matthew 9:17 — "Neither do men put new wine into old bottles: else the bottles break, and the wine runneth out, and the bottles perish: but they put new wine into new bottles, and both are preserved."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 9, 'adults', 1, 'What is the theological connection between Jesus forgiving sins and healing the paralytic (9:2-6)?', 'Jesus demonstrates his authority to forgive sins (the greater miracle) by performing the visible physical healing (the lesser but verifiable miracle)', 'Physical healing always precedes spiritual forgiveness in Jesus'' ministry', 'Sin and sickness are always directly connected in Matthew', 'The healing was performed primarily as a demonstration for the crowd', 'a', 'Matthew 9:5-6 — "For whether is easier, to say, Thy sins be forgiven thee; or to say, Arise, and walk? But that ye may know that the Son of man hath power on earth to forgive sins, (then saith he to the sick of the palsy,) Arise, take up thy bed." The physical healing provides visible proof of the invisible spiritual authority.'),
('Matthew', 9, 'adults', 2, 'Jesus says he desires "mercy, and not sacrifice" (9:13), quoting Hosea 6:6. How does this rebuke the Pharisees'' complaint about eating with sinners?', 'The Pharisees prioritized cultic purity/separation over compassionate engagement with sinners — inverting the prophetic priority of mercy', 'Jesus is abolishing the sacrificial system entirely', 'The Pharisees were right that Jesus should not eat with sinners', 'Hosea 6:6 is misapplied — it refers only to temple worship', 'a', 'Matthew 9:12-13 — Jesus quotes Hosea 6:6 to rebuke the Pharisees'' table-fellowship objections. The prophets repeatedly called Israel back from ritual religiosity to covenant mercy (hesed); Jesus applies this to his mission of calling sinners.'),
('Matthew', 9, 'adults', 3, 'What does the double healing account (Jairus''s daughter + the bleeding woman) accomplish literarily and theologically?', 'Matthew sandwiches one healing within another (intercalation), showing both a ritually unclean woman and a dead child restored — boundary-crossing compassion', 'The two healings are unrelated and placed together only for chronological reasons', 'The bleeding woman''s healing is used as a negative example', 'Both healings demonstrate only the power of physical faith objects', 'a', 'Matthew 9:18-26 — The interruption of one miracle story by another (intercalation) is a Markan technique Matthew preserves. Both subjects (a ritually unclean woman and a corpse) would have made Jesus ceremonially impure, yet his touch brings life rather than acquiring defilement.'),
('Matthew', 9, 'adults', 4, 'What is the significance of Jesus'' phrase "the Son of man hath power on earth to forgive sins" (9:6)?', '"Son of Man" from Daniel 7 — the one given dominion — here exercises divine prerogative of forgiveness on earth, a remarkable Christological claim', 'It means Jesus could only forgive sins during his earthly ministry', 'Son of Man is merely a term for human beings in general', 'Jesus is asserting that all humans have the power to forgive', 'a', 'Matthew 9:6 — The "Son of Man" title connects to Daniel 7:13-14 where one like a son of man receives dominion from the Ancient of Days. Jesus'' claim to forgive sins "on earth" is an implicit claim to divine authority exercised in his incarnate ministry.'),
('Matthew', 9, 'adults', 5, 'The mocking laughter at the news that the girl is only sleeping (9:24) contrasts with the crowd''s amazement after the resurrection (9:25-26). What does this structure teach?', 'Unbelief mocks what faith receives; the crowd''s limited perception contrasts with the disciples'' witness of actual resurrection power', 'Jesus deliberately misled the crowd by saying she was sleeping', 'The crowd was correct that the girl was only in a coma', 'Matthew includes the laughter to show the disciples'' weakness', 'a', 'Matthew 9:24 — "And they laughed him to scorn." Verse 25 — "And when the people were put forth, he went in, and took her by the hand, and the maid arose." The removal of the mockers and the private resurrection miracle (also with no crowd) pattern repeats in Jesus'' own resurrection witness structure.'),
('Matthew', 9, 'adults', 6, 'What does the harvest/laborer metaphor (9:37-38) reveal about Jesus'' understanding of his mission''s scope?', 'The harvest is plenteous but laborers are few — the mission requires prayer and more workers; the world''s need far exceeds current capacity', 'The harvest is nearly complete and few more workers are needed', 'The metaphor means only a remnant of Israel will be saved', 'Jesus is preparing the disciples to remain in Galilee only', 'a', 'Matthew 9:37-38 — "The harvest truly is plenteous, but the labourers are few; Pray ye therefore the Lord of the harvest, that he will send forth labourers into his harvest." This prepares for the mission of the Twelve in chapter 10 and ultimately the Great Commission in chapter 28.'),
('Matthew', 9, 'adults', 7, 'How does Jesus'' description of Israel as "sheep having no shepherd" (9:36) echo the OT critique of failed leadership?', 'It echoes Numbers 27:17, Ezekiel 34, and Zechariah 10:2 — God''s people scattered for lack of faithful shepherds, Jesus as the true shepherd', 'It refers only to the physical wandering of Galilean peasants', 'It is a criticism of Roman governance', 'It describes only the Sadducees who denied resurrection', 'a', 'Matthew 9:36 — "he saw the multitudes, he was moved with compassion on them, because they fainted, and were scattered abroad, as sheep having no shepherd." Num 27:17 uses this exact phrase for Israel without Moses; Ezekiel 34 extensively develops the failed shepherd theme Jesus fulfills.'),
('Matthew', 9, 'adults', 8, 'What is the significance of the healing of the mute demoniac (9:32-34) prompting the Pharisees to accuse Jesus of casting out demons by "the prince of the devils"?', 'It anticipates the Beelzebub controversy (ch.12) and shows the Pharisees'' hardening rejection of Jesus despite clear evidence — attributing divine works to Satan', 'The Pharisees were open to reconsidering if more evidence were provided', 'The accusation was a reasonable alternative explanation of the miracle', 'The Pharisees were primarily concerned with maintaining Roman political relationships', 'a', 'Matthew 9:34 — "But the Pharisees said, He casteth out devils through the prince of the devils." This marks the beginning of the Pharisees'' formal opposition based on demonizing Jesus'' power, which reaches its climax in the unforgivable sin passage of Matthew 12:24-32.');

-- ═══ Matthew Chapter 10 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Matthew', 10, 'kids', 1, 'How many disciples did Jesus send out in Matthew 10?', 'Twelve', 'Seven', 'Seventy', 'Three', 'a', 'Matthew 10:1 — "And when he had called unto him his twelve disciples, he gave them power against unclean spirits, to cast them out, and to heal all manner of sickness and all manner of disease."'),
('Matthew', 10, 'kids', 2, 'Jesus told the disciples to be wise as serpents and harmless as what?', 'Doves', 'Lambs', 'Children', 'Sparrows', 'a', 'Matthew 10:16 — "be ye therefore wise as serpents, and harmless as doves."'),
('Matthew', 10, 'kids', 3, 'Are sparrows worth much money? What does Jesus say about sparrows?', 'Two sparrows are sold for a farthing but God knows when even one falls', 'Sparrows are not worth anything to God', 'Sparrows represent evil in the kingdom', 'Sparrows are the birds God loves most', 'a', 'Matthew 10:29 — "Are not two sparrows sold for a farthing? and one of them shall not fall on the ground without your Father."'),
-- Teens
('Matthew', 10, 'teens', 1, 'To whom did Jesus primarily send the twelve disciples on this first mission?', 'The lost sheep of the house of Israel', 'All the nations of the world', 'The Samaritans first, then the Gentiles', 'The synagogues of Judaea only', 'a', 'Matthew 10:6 — "But go rather to the lost sheep of the house of Israel."'),
('Matthew', 10, 'teens', 2, 'What does Jesus say will happen to the disciple and the servant compared to their master?', 'It is enough for the disciple to be as his master and the servant as his lord', 'The disciple will always be greater than the master', 'The servant will suffer less than the master', 'The disciple will replace the master in time', 'a', 'Matthew 10:25 — "It is enough for the disciple that he be as his master, and the servant as his lord."'),
('Matthew', 10, 'teens', 3, 'What does Jesus say he came to bring — not peace but what?', 'A sword', 'Fire', 'Judgment', 'Separation', 'a', 'Matthew 10:34 — "Think not that I am come to send peace on earth: I came not to send peace, but a sword."'),
('Matthew', 10, 'teens', 4, 'What will happen to the one who loses his life for Jesus'' sake?', 'He will find it', 'He will be rewarded in the resurrection', 'He will receive a crown of life', 'He will be remembered by God', 'a', 'Matthew 10:39 — "He that findeth his life shall lose it: and he that loseth his life for my sake shall find it."'),
('Matthew', 10, 'teens', 5, 'What happens to the person who receives a disciple in Jesus'' name?', 'He receives Jesus, and he who receives Jesus receives the Father who sent him', 'He receives a special blessing but not Jesus himself', 'He is considered a disciple by association', 'He must also leave everything to follow Jesus', 'a', 'Matthew 10:40-41 — "He that receiveth you receiveth me, and he that receiveth me receiveth him that sent me."'),
-- Adults
('Matthew', 10, 'adults', 1, 'What is the theological basis for the disciples receiving no payment in the instruction "freely ye have received, freely give" (10:8)?', 'The kingdom''s gifts (healing, deliverance, proclamation) are God''s grace and cannot be commodified — workers are sustained by the community they serve', 'The disciples were already wealthy enough', 'It means miracles are not real but symbolic', 'Payment for ministry was forbidden only in Jewish contexts', 'a', 'Matthew 10:8 — "Heal the sick, cleanse the lepers, raise the dead, cast out devils: freely ye have received, freely give." The grace of the kingdom cannot be sold; this contrasts with false teachers who exploit the flock for financial gain (Micah 3:11).'),
('Matthew', 10, 'adults', 2, 'What is the significance of the instruction to shake the dust off one''s feet (10:14)?', 'A prophetic sign of judgment — like shaking off Gentile dust when re-entering Israel — symbolizing that the rejecting city is treated as pagan ground', 'A hygienic practice with no symbolic meaning', 'A sign of blessing to the town rejected', 'An instruction to physically remove soil from sandals for cleanliness', 'a', 'Matthew 10:14 — "And whosoever shall not receive you, nor hear your words, when ye depart out of that house or city, shake off the dust of your feet." Jews shook off Gentile dust when returning to Israel; applying this to Jewish cities is a profound prophetic judgment sign.'),
('Matthew', 10, 'adults', 3, 'How does the instruction to be "wise as serpents" and "harmless as doves" (10:16) hold two virtues in tension?', 'Serpentine wisdom (strategic discernment about hostile environments) must be balanced by dove-like innocence (moral purity without guile)', 'Wisdom means cunning deception and harmlessness means silence', 'The two qualities apply to different disciples', 'It is a folk proverb with no specific theological meaning', 'a', 'Matthew 10:16 — In a hostile mission environment, disciples need both qualities simultaneously: the situational awareness and prudence of serpents and the moral transparency and peace-seeking of doves. Neither alone is sufficient.'),
('Matthew', 10, 'adults', 4, 'What does Jesus'' promise "it shall be given you in that same hour what ye shall speak" (10:19) teach about the Holy Spirit''s role in witness?', 'Under direct persecution, the Spirit will provide the testimony needed — the disciples are not solely reliant on their own preparation', 'The Spirit removes all need for preparation or Bible knowledge', 'This promise applies only to the twelve apostles at Pentecost', 'It means Christians should never prepare sermons', 'a', 'Matthew 10:19-20 — "But when they deliver you up, take no thought how or what ye shall speak: for it shall be given you in that same hour what ye shall speak. For it is not ye that speak, but the Spirit of your Father which speaketh in you."'),
('Matthew', 10, 'adults', 5, 'Jesus says in 10:28 to fear God who can destroy both soul and body in Gehenna. What is the significance of Gehenna as a term?', 'Gehenna (Valley of Hinnom) was a place of child sacrifice and later Jerusalem''s garbage dump — used by Jesus as an image of final divine judgment', 'Gehenna means only temporary suffering before purgatory', 'Gehenna refers to the Roman underworld concept of Hades', 'Gehenna is a metaphor for social exclusion from community', 'a', 'Matthew 10:28 — "but rather fear him which is able to destroy both soul and body in hell (Gehenna)." The Valley of Hinnom (Ge Hinnom → Gehenna) was Israel''s most defiled place; Jesus uses it to describe the reality of final judgment that should recalibrate all earthly fear.'),
('Matthew', 10, 'adults', 6, 'What is the Christological implication of Jesus'' statement "He that receiveth me receiveth him that sent me" (10:40)?', 'Jesus and the Father are in such unity that reception of the Son constitutes reception of the Father — an implicit claim to divine oneness', 'It means Jesus was merely a messenger like OT prophets', 'It teaches that the Father and Son are separate beings of different status', 'It applies only to reception by Israel, not Gentiles', 'a', 'Matthew 10:40 — "He that receiveth you receiveth me, and he that receiveth me receiveth him that sent me." The chain of reception (disciple → Jesus → Father) implies a unity of identity and purpose between Jesus and the Father that goes beyond a mere prophetic messenger relationship.'),
('Matthew', 10, 'adults', 7, 'How does Jesus'' saying about bringing a sword and dividing families (10:34-36) relate to Micah 7:6?', 'Matthew 10:35-36 directly quotes or alludes to Micah 7:6 — showing that messianic crisis was prophesied to create division even within households', 'Jesus is correcting Micah''s pessimistic view of family', 'The sword saying has no OT precedent and is purely situational', 'Micah 7:6 refers to the Assyrian invasion, not the messianic age', 'a', 'Matthew 10:35-36 quotes Micah 7:6 — "For I am come to set a man at variance against his father, and the daughter against her mother...And a man''s foes shall be they of his own household." Micah anticipated that faithfulness to God would divide families in the messianic crisis.'),
('Matthew', 10, 'adults', 8, 'What does the promise of a reward for giving "a cup of cold water" to a little one "in the name of a disciple" (10:42) teach about kingdom economics?', 'The smallest act of hospitality done in solidarity with Jesus'' disciples carries eternal weight — the kingdom reverses the world''s valuation of great versus small acts', 'Only large donations and sacrifices are rewarded', 'The reward is purely social recognition in the community', 'Cold water is symbolic of the Holy Spirit''s gifts', 'a', 'Matthew 10:42 — "And whosoever shall give to drink unto one of these little ones a cup of cold water only in the name of a disciple, verily I say unto you, he shall in no wise lose his reward." The "only" emphasizes that even the smallest act of kingdom solidarity is eternally significant.');
